Facing Grief by Rodney Howard Browne
A couple of you reading these words didn't release your kids in this way. Perhaps you have lost your child through death, a hideous crime, divorce, or another ugly crisis. God failed to find pleasure in making you endure such grief. Yes, as with Job, he permitted it, but he isn't the writer of malignant. The noxious wish of a world that has been twisted by sin took your kid from you. He detests it so much that He sent His Boy to damage death by dying and rising again. Death is sometimes known as in the Scriptures our "last enemy" ( one Corinthians 15:26 ). Put simply : Death is the will of a world gone wrong. Whether we lose our youngsters by crisis or design, this much is true : Anything we hold dear, we must learn the way to hold loosely. Let's come clean, if we hold anything too forcefully, it most likely has us rather than our having it. And God will not permit that for your sake or the sake of your loved. Human instinct would have us clutch the stuff we like most. Releasing them, presenting them to God, cites that we trust Him to do what's right. When we do this for our youngsters, the lasting impact we leave is a practical model of faith. And I can think about no neater way to train our youngsters about the God we worship than by modeling our trust in Him daily.
